 that cannot be conveniently forgotten, and memory is the only court that endures. If the breath must enter a cord, then it must do so by witnessed measure, with loops that forbid strangulation and knots that refuse to bind the throat of the poor. Give me the braid to hold, and make your argument not to power but to precedent, and I will sign where the city can read its own mercy without going blind.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Safra Ninebridges\", \"lines\": \"I will sign a bridge over a river I cannot own if I am allowed to keep my feet on both banks and not be pushed into the current by either. My people brought bread and coal in winters when your gates froze, and we asked for tolls you could afford because we intended to come back again in the spring. Thread this cord so it hears salt on the tongue, and song in the rope-lines, not only your tallies etched by silent hands in quiet halls. A city that forgets its roads forgets its lungs, and a throat that closes itself does not sing but chokes. Show me a clause that protects the wayfarer, the peddler, and the child who sleeps on a wagon plank, and I will teach my grandchildren that this was the day Marrowgate remembered who carried it when it was still too small to walk.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Avar Ir\", \"lines\": \"The kilns do not feed themselves, and a city that scorns its furnaces will eat glass in its bread and ash in its sleep, because neglect is always swallowed last and longest. I do not ask that we pour this breath into our chimneys or our retorts, for even I know a taboo that keeps us a people and not a furnace that learned to speak. But bind a promise that when the heat rises we will share it by rule and not by riot, and that ash will be weighed by justice and not by jealousy. Give industry a voice in the braid and we will temper our flame to the city’s song, annealing strength rather than shattering it with sudden temperature. Let the Accord remember that bellies are not warmed by hymns alone, a